tes exceed those of the United States, the reverse is true for the crucial years between elementary school and college. After providing a history of Fidel Castro's educational revolution begun in 1953, Denise Blum delivers a close examination of the effects of the program, which was designed to produce a society motivated by benevolence rather than materialism. Exploring pioneering pedagogy, the notion of civic education, and the rural components of the program, Cuban Youth and Revolutionary Values brims with surprising findings about one of the most intriguing social experiments in recent history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEducation -- Cuba -- Evaluation. 0aEducation -- Cuba -- History. 0aEducation -- Curricula -- Cuba. 0aEducationxCurriculazCuba. 0aEducationzCubaxEvaluation. 0aEducationzCubaxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784833/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK